Subject: [MSN] Oslo court sentences three in theft of Munch paintings
To: Museum Security Network Mailinglist <msn-list@te.verweg.com>
Message-ID: <462D8C8E.7070202@bruggemansolutions.com>
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8; format=flowed


  Oslo court sentences three in theft of Munch paintings


        Published: 24 April 2007

An Oslo appeals court sentenced three men to prison terms of up to nine 
and a half years yesterday for their roles in the 2004 theft of the 
Edvard Munch masterpieces "The Scream" and "Madonna."

The paintings, which were insured for 750 million kroner (US$125 
million), were recovered by police on 31 August, just over two years 
after they were stolen by masked gunmen in a brazen daylight heist at 
Oslo's Munch Museum. Both were damaged and are undergoing repairs.

The three defendants were also ordered to jointly pay 1.57 million 
kroner (US$262 million) in compensation to the City of Oslo, which owns 
the paintings.

There are four versions of "The Scream," probably Munch's best-known 
work, depicting a waif-like figure apparently screaming or hearing a 
scream. The image has become an icon of modern human anxiety.

In late March, the Borgarting appeals court in Oslo found the three men 
guilty of helping the armed robbers, and acquitted three others.

"There has to be a sharp reaction to such a serious crime," the court 
said during sentencing, describing the paintings as "two of the 
cornerstones of Munch's production." Police also suspect that the 
robbery was organized to draw police resources away from a 2004 bank 
robbery in which a police officer was killed.

Petter Tharaldsen, 35, was sentenced to nine-and-a-half years in prison 
for driving the getaway car that spirited off the paintings and robbers. 
His term also included a sentence for an unrelated robbery.

Bjoern Hoen, 39, convicted of masterminding the theft, was sentenced to 
nine years for grand theft. Tharaldsen and Hoen were also convicted of 
being part of an organized crime group.

Stian Skjold, 31, was sentenced to five and a half years as one of the 
two gunmen who raided the Munch Museum. The second suspected gunman died 
in November before charges were brought against him.

"I will advise my client to appeal. The sentence is much too long," 
Morten Furuholmen, who defended Skjold, was quoted as telling the 
Norwegian news agency NTB. The other two defense lawyers and the 
prosecution said they would review the ruling before deciding on appeals.

Prosecutor Elisabeth Ramstad said she was satisfied that the court had 
completely accepted her description of the suspects roles and other 
facts in the case.

Police have refused to say how they recovered the paintings, which 
suffered scrapes, holes, loose paint and moisture damage. The museum is 
considering using an eye-surgeon to remove tiny fragments of glass 
embedded in the works after their frames were broken.

Munch's emotionally charged painting style became a major influence in 
the birth of the 20th-century expressionist movement. Munch died in 1944 
at the age of 80.

http://news.independent.co.uk/




